    "narrative": "The Austin Waves enter today\u2019s slate with high-ceiling opportunities concentrated at the top of the order, headlined by **Jackson Merrill** (67.22) and **Jacob Wilson** (64.91). **Jackson Merrill** benefits significantly from a favorable dynamic platoon split against a right-handed starter and his projected #2 spot in the order, effectively offsetting the challenge of facing a high-caliber arm. Similarly, **Jacob Wilson** receives a double-boost from a hitter-friendly park environment and the fact that he is elevated to the #5 spot, providing him the leverage needed to maximize his efficiency. **Vladimir Guerrero Jr.** (63.81) remains a constant anchor, and while his platoon split is slightly negative against this right-handed opponent, his elite xwOBA of .384 keeps his daily floor exceptionally stable.\n\nWe are navigating a few tactical hurdles today, specifically regarding **Gunnar Henderson** (48.62) and **Josh Lowe** (41.11). **Gunnar Henderson** is currently flagged with a 44% rain risk, and facing a tough left-handed arm suppresses his projected efficiency significantly despite his premium batting order position. **Josh Lowe** presents the lowest score in our active lineup, dragged down by a poor matchup against a pitcher with an elite ability to hold runners, which complicates his path to providing value in our scarcest category: stolen bases. The closest call on the bench was **Miguel Vargas** (49.72), who narrowly missed the cut; while his #1 batting order position is appealing, the optimizer opted for the higher raw efficiency of the active starters, keeping **Miguel Vargas** in a reserve role to avoid unnecessary depletion of our game caps.\n\nBeyond the starters, we must monitor the status of **Gunnar Henderson** and **Coby Mayo** closely due to the aforementioned weather concerns. If the game in Baltimore is postponed, we have the flexibility to pivot, though we are wary of over-exposure to pitchers like the one facing **Josh Low